# 0. OVERARCHING MISSION
# ----------------------
# Build a secure, maintainable, scalable, testable platform.
# Use AI as assistant — but never as a substitute for human review or judgment.

# 1. PROJECT STRUCTURE & MODULE ORGANIZATION
- All source code must reside under /src (never at project root).  
- Code must follow layered/module-based architecture: config, routes, controllers, services, models/repositories, middlewares, utils, validators, integrations, jobs, tests.  
- No “god-files”: avoid dumping many unrelated functions in a single file — files should be logically cohesive.  
- Folder and filename conventions must match agreed naming rules (e.g. kebab-case/folder-name, camelCase functions/variables, PascalCase for types/classes).  


# 2. TYPE SAFETY, LINTING & FORMATTING
- Project must be TypeScript-based. All new code must compile with no TypeScript errors.  
- ESLint + Prettier (or equivalent) must be configured and respected.  
- All commits must pass linting & formatting rules before merge (use pre-commit or CI).  

# 3. ERROR HANDLING & STABILITY
- All asynchronous operations must use async/await (no raw callbacks).  
- Use a centralised error-handling mechanism; custom error classes for different error types (Validation, Auth, External, etc.).  
- Do not leak internal error details or stack traces to external clients — send sanitized, safe messages.  

# 4. SECURITY & INPUT VALIDATION
- ALWAYS validate and sanitise all external inputs (HTTP body, query, params).  
- Use secure HTTP headers, enable HTTPS in production, use secure cookies or tokens, avoid trusted user input.  
- No hard-coded secrets, credentials, or API keys in code — always use environment variables or secure vaults.  
- Rate-limit sensitive endpoints (auth, file upload/download, external-API proxy).  

# 5. TESTING & CI-GATED QUALITY
- Every new feature or module must include automated tests (unit and/or integration).  
- On each commit or pull-request: lint → type-check → compile → run tests → only merge if all pass.  
- For critical flows (auth, data, integrations): adopt test-first or test-driven development.  

# 6. DOCUMENTATION & Governance
- Every module/folder must include a README or doc comment summarising purpose, inputs/outputs, dependencies.  
- Maintain central project README + CONTRIBUTING + AGENTS + architecture documentation.  
- For any significant change (schema, major feature, architecture), update docs accordingly.  
- Maintain a “tech-debt/issue backlog” for deferred work (TODOs, known limitations, clean-up).  

# 7. AI-ASSISTED DEVELOPMENT RULES
- AI tools (Cursor/Codex) may be used — but **human review + tests + lint + docs update** are mandatory before merging any AI-generated code.  
- Provide AI with up-to-date project context (folder structure, naming, rules, documentation) — keep AGENTS.md current.  
- For major structural changes: re-index project context so AI does not rely on stale assumptions.  
- Prefer Test-Driven workflow when using AI — write tests/spec first, then prompt AI to implement.  

# 8. DEPENDENCY & SECURITY MAINTENANCE
- Use lockfile for dependencies (package-lock or equivalent).  
- Periodically run dependency vulnerability audits; upgrade dependencies with tests and QA.  
- Evaluate each new dependency carefully — avoid “just because it exists” mentality.  

# 9. DEPLOYMENT & OPERATIONS READINESS
- Provide config to separate environments (development, staging, production).  
- Ensure logging is structured (e.g. JSON), avoid printing secrets.  
- Implement health-check endpoints (e.g. `/health`, `/ready`) to support deployment orchestration or monitoring.  
- Use containerization (e.g. Docker) for consistent deployment environments.  

# 10. PROHIBITED PRACTICES
- No inline/raw database queries — always use ORM / safe query builder.  
- No dynamic code execution (eval, dynamic require, unsanitised path operations).  
- No hard-coded credentials/secrets in code.  
- No merging of unreviewed AI-generated code.  
- No unchecked bypass of input validation / sanitisation.  
- No monolithic files with unrelated responsibilities (avoid “god-classes” or “god-modules”).  

# =====================================================================
# END OF CURSOR-RULES
